Learning Objectives

  • Solve a system of linear equations using the backslash operator in MATLAB.

Systems of Linear Equations in MATLAB

Systems of linear equations consist of coefficients, constants, and variables, which can be arranged into matrices. The matrix form to express a system of linear equations is matrix A for the coefficients, matrix x for the variables, and matrix b for the constants, which yields the formula . Solving for the variables involves taking the transpose of A multiplied by b, or . Solving for the variables of a system of linear equations in MATLAB involves using the backslash operator, \
will return the solution to .

Worked Example

For example, let's look at the following system of linear equations.
First, separate the constant terms and the variable terms resulting the following system of linear equations.
Second, create the coefficient matrix A. Each row of the coefficient matrix represents the coefficients of one of the linear equations and each column represents the coefficients of one of the variables across all three linear equations. A has the same number of rows and columns, which is equal to the total unknown variables and the number of equations in the system.
A = [-3 4 2;
1 6 -4;
-2 -5 -8]
A = 3×3
-3 4 2 1 6 -4 -2 -5 -8
Next, create column vector of constant terms, matrix b. Each row of the column vector represents the isolated constant term of a linear equation.
Note: The order of the represented linear equations is arbitrary but should match the order of the rows seen in the coefficient matrix.
b = [9;
7;
4]
b = 3×1
9 7 4
Finally, use the backslash operator to solve for the values of , , and . The solution will take the form of a column vector, x, with the first, second, and third rows representing the values of , , and respectively.
x = A\b
x = 3×1
-2.0213 1.0638 -0.6596
Note: If the first and second column of the coefficient matrix a were exchanged, the solution would take the form of a column vector, x, with the first, second, and third rows representing the values of , , and respectively. The order of the columns in the coefficient matrix determines the order of the rows in the solution vector.
A = [ 4 -3 2;
6 1 -4;
-5 -2 -8];
 
b = [9;
7;
4];
 
x = A\b
x = 3×1
1.0638 -2.0213 -0.6596

Further Practice and Interactive Coding Template for Homework

To get additional practice solving systems of linear equations, we have provided a MATLAB live script titled Systems_of_Linear_Equations.mlx, with the same worked example as above and an interactive example. The corresponding solution to the interactive example is available in Systems_of_Linear_Equations_sol.mlx. We also have created an explanatory youtube video: Solving Systems of Linear Equations Using a MATLAB Live Script
You are encouraged to edit Systems_of_Linear_Equations.mlx as an interactive coding template for solving homework problems.
